06720nam a22009615i 9783110780741DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2022931827  a97831107807417 a10.1515/97831107807412doi  a(DE-B1597)614021  a(OCoLC)1322123931  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aREL0061002bisacsh00aExperiencing the Shepherd of Hermas /ced. by Angela Kim Harkins, Harry O. Maier. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (XII, 275 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEkstasis: Religious Experience from Antiquity to the Middle Ages ,x1865-8792 ;v1000tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbbreviations -- tForeword -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tI The Shepherd, the Self, and Subjectivity -- tNegotiating the Experience of Possession in Hermas’s Shepherd -- tA True Prophet as a Mouthpiece of the Spirit? Cultivating Virtue and Control -- tGender, Volubility, and Transformation in the Shepherd of Hermas -- tThe Affect and Happy Objects of the Shepherd of Hermas -- tII Visions and Experiences of the Divine -- tPsychotropic Elements in Hermas’s First Two Visions: Between Experience and Culture -- tEntering the Narrative World of Hermas’s Visions -- tExperience through Narrative in the Shepherd of Hermas -- tShepherd of Hermas Vision 5 and the Christian Experience of Pagan Epiphany -- tGod’s Multiple Forms: Divine Fluidity in the Shepherd of Hermas -- tIII Experiencing the Shepherd as Text -- tThe Former Slave Hermas, Lady Church and ‘the Book’ -- tAuthority, Fragmentation, Dilution: Experiencing an Apocalyptic Text in Late Antiquity -- tBibliography -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex of Subjects -- tAncient Text Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Shepherd of Hermas is one of the oldest and most well-attested Christian works. Its popularity arguably exceeded that of the canonical Gospels. Many early Christian thinkers regarded the Shepherd as authoritative and cited it in their own writings, even though its status as Scripture was controversial. The far-reaching influence of the Shepherd during the first few centuries is attested in part by the many languages in which it was copied: Latin, Ethiopic, Coptic, Middle Persian, and Georgian. The early dating and wide dissemination of the Shepherd of Hermas offers us access to a period when canonical boundaries were elastic. This volume treats religious experience in the Shepherd, a topic that has received little scholarly attention. It complements a growing body of literature that explores the text from social-historical perspectives. Leading scholars approach it from a variety of interdisciplinary perspectives, including critical literary theory, anthropology, cognitive science, affect theory, gender studies, intersectionality, and text reception. In doing so, they pose fresh questions to one of the most widely read texts in the early church, offering new insights to scholars and students alike.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aHermas. 4aProphetentum. 4aReligiöse Erfahrung. 4aVisionen. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / New Testament.2bisacsh  aProphecy.  aSelf / Subjectivity.  areligious experience.  avisions.1 aArcari, Luca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBatovici, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBazzana, Giovanni B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChoi, Jung H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCombs, Jason Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb